{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For each category, a facility within the ideal distance gets a perfect sub-score. Beyond the ideal, the score decays linearly to zero at a maximum distance threshold (20 km for hospitals, 5-8 km for the others). If a POI type doesn\u8217't exist nearby at all, that sub-score is zero \u8211- we treat the absence of a nearby hospital as genuinely bad, not just unknown.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Hospitals carry the most weight because emergency access is the highest-stakes proximity factor for senior residents.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b High score (80-95):} All four POI types within their ideal distances. {\b Low score (0-20):} Most POIs beyond their maximum thresholds.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Leadership (10% of composite)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Evaluates the ownership behind a facility across three dimensions:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Entity type (30% within category):} What kind of organization owns the facility? Nonprofits score highest (mission-aligned with care), followed by individuals (personal accountability), then LLCs, corporations, and REITs (investment-driven structures tend to distance ownership from operations).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Geographic locality (35% within category):} Where is the owner based relative to Washington state? In-state owners score highest, neighboring states next, then decreasing scores for more distant states. Local ownership suggests closer operational involvement.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Operational stability (35% within category):} How long has the owning entity been in business? Entities operating 7+ years score highest. Newly incorporated entities (under 1 year) score lowest. Longevity suggests operational maturity.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When a sub-dimension has no data (e.g., we can\u8217't determine where the owner is based), its weight redistributes to the sub-dimensions we do have data for.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b High score (80+):} Nonprofit, based in Washington, operating 7+ years. {\b Low score (25-40):} REIT or unknown entity, out-of-state, newly incorporated.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Brand (5% of composite)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The lightest category, measuring operator reputation across their portfolio of facilities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Two factors:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Track record (70% within category):} The median composite score across all other facilities the same operator runs. If an operator\u8217's other facilities score well, that\u8217's a positive signal for this one.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Portfolio size (30% within category):} How many facilities the operator manages. Larger portfolios suggest institutional systems and processes, though this is a weaker signal than actual performance.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Track record carries the bulk of the weight because past performance across the portfolio is more meaningful than size alone. A small operator with excellent facilities outscores a large chain with mediocre ones.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This category returns no score on the first scoring run (since cross-facility data hasn\u8217't been computed yet), and its 5% weight redistributes to the other categories.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b High score (75-95):} Large portfolio with high median scores across facilities. {\b Low score (0-30):} Single facility or small operator with poor peer performance.\par}
